#Text=Henry Nevill , 6th Baron Bergavenny
#Text=Henry Nevill , 6th and de jure 4th Baron Abergavenny KB ( between 1527 and 1535 – 10 February 1587 ) was an English peer .
#Text=He was the son of Sir George Nevill , 5th Baron Bergavenny , and Mary Stafford ( daughter of Edward Stafford , 3rd Duke of Buckingham ) .
#Text=He succeeded to the barony upon the death of his father , George Nevill , 5th Baron Bergavenny .
#Text=Biography
#Text=Henry , sixth ( sometimes fourth ) Lord Abergavenny , had summons to parliament on 23 January 1552 , to 15 October 1586 .
#Text=He was one of the peers that sat in judgment on Mary , Queen of Scots , at Fotheringay .
#Text=He died at his seat called Comfort , near Birling , Kent , on 10 February 1587 .

#Text=He married first , Frances , daughter of Thomas Manners , 1st Earl of Rutland ; he married secondly , Elizabeth , daughter of Stephen Darell , of Spelmonden , Kent ( she remarried to Sir William Sedley , of Southfleet , Kent , Knt . and Bart . ) ; by his first wife , he had an only daughter Mary Neville who married Sir Thomas Fane .
#Text=Wyatt 's rebellion
#Text=During the Wyatt 's rebellion of January – February 1554
#Text=Henry and Robert Southwell , the High Sheriff of Kent married to Henry 's niece Margaret , led the loyalist forces against the rebels .
#Text=According to D. M. Loades , " Sir Robert Southwell and Lord Abergavenny were almost the only significant gentlemen in the country whose loyalty was never in doubt " ; [ 1 ]
#Text=" Southwell , Abergavenny and Cheney were the most active royalist leaders . " [ 2 ]
#Text=Henry and Southwell began recruitment of loyalist forces on 24 January , one day before the outbreak of the rebellion , although at this stage they had little success . [ 3 ]
#Text=On 26 January Wyatt declared Henry and Southwell " traitors to God , the Crown and the Commonwealth " for " stirring up the Queen 's most loyal subjects of the realm . " [ 4 ]
#Text=By 27 January the loyalists 's position improved , and their combined forces in Kent matched the numbers of Wyatt 's force in Rochester , at around two thousand men on each side . [ 5 ]
#Text=Henry and Southwell with six hundred men blocked the road from Tonbridge to Rochester to prevent consolidation of the rebels . [ 5 ]
#Text=On 28 January Southwell defeated Henry Isley 's company of rebels at Wrotham , taking around sixty prisoners . [ 6 ]
#Text=However , on the same day the army of Duke of Norfolk deserted to Wyatt ; [ 7 ]
#Text=Henry and Southwell fled to London . [ 8 ]

#Text=Wyatt marched to London himself with around three thousand men , [ 9 ] but lost the initiative ; Southwell and Thomas Cheney managed to raise another loyalist company in his rear . [ 10 ] [ 11 ]
#Text=On 4 February Henry and Southwell marched to Greenwich .
#Text=Wyatt was cut off from his base in Kent , and could not count on reinforcements while the loyalists ' forces gained strength every day . [ 11 ]
#Text=By 7 February Wyatt 's army disintegrated .
#Text=Amongst Wyatt 's supporters who were later sentenced to death was Thomas Fane , later Henry Nevill 's son in law .
#Text=Fane was pardoned due to his youth and he went on to become a loyal supporter of the crown , member of parliament and son in law to Neville .
#Text=Issue

#Text=Mary Neville , Baroness le Despencer , died 28 June 1626 , aged 72 , buried at Mereworth , Kent , having married at Birling , 12 December 1574 , as second wife , to Thomas Fane , of Badsell , Kent [ 12 ] ( whose son , Francis , was created Earl of Westmorland ) , knighted at Dover Castle , 26 August 1573 , died 13 March 1589 , w. d. 12 March 1589 , pd . 10 February 1590 .

#Text=Lady Fane claimed the barony of Abergavenny against Edward Nevill , the heir male upon whom the castle of Bergavenny was settled as aforesaid , and as a compromise , she was by letters patent , 25 May 1604 , confirmed in the name , style , and dignity of Baroness le Despencer , to the heirs of her body , with the ancient seat , place , and precedence of her ancestors .
#Text=Ancestry
